          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In glaucoma, sustained elevation of intraocular pressure leads to vision loss primarily by damaging which structure?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The corneal endothelium at the limbus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. While acutely raised IOP can cause corneal oedema, the primary mechanism of irreversible vision loss in glaucoma is damage to the optic nerve, not the cornea.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The optic nerve at the posterior pole of the eye</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Sustained raised IOP damages nerve fibres at the lamina cribrosa, leading to progressive optic atrophy and irreversible visual field loss.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The retinal pigment epithelium</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The retinal pigment epithelium is affected in conditions like age-related macular degeneration. Glaucoma specifically damages the optic nerve through sustained pressure.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The lens capsule and zonular fibres</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. Lens capsule pathology relates to cataract formation. In glaucoma, it is the optic nerve that suffers irreversible damage from chronically raised pressure.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The correct answer is the optic nerve. In glaucoma, raised IOP damages nerve fibres at the lamina cribrosa. This causes progressive visual field loss that is irreversible once established."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The optic nerve is the target of glaucomatous damage — remember that the lamina cribrosa is the weakest point of the sclera, where elevated pressure does the most harm."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
