          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>In a third cranial nerve palsy, the pupil becomes fixed and dilated because of p</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In a third cranial nerve palsy, the pupil becomes fixed and dilated because of paralysis of which intraocular muscle?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Dilator pupillae</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The dilator pupillae receives sympathetic supply and widens the pupil. In CN III palsy, this muscle is intact — it acts unopposed because its antagonist (sphincter pupillae) is paralysed.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ciliary muscle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The ciliary muscle is also parasympathetically supplied via CN III and its paralysis causes cycloplegia (loss of accommodation), but the fixed dilated pupil results specifically from sphincter pupillae paralysis.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sphincter pupillae</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The sphincter pupillae constricts the pupil via parasympathetic fibres from CN III. These fibres run on the nerve's surface and are compressed first, producing an early fixed dilated pupil.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Superior tarsal muscle</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Incorrect. The superior tarsal muscle (Müller's muscle) is sympathetically innervated and contributes to lid elevation. Its loss causes the partial ptosis of Horner's syndrome, not pupil dilation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The correct answer is the sphincter pupillae. It constricts the pupil via parasympathetic fibres from CN III. When these surface-running fibres are compressed, the pupil dilates because the sympathetically-driven dilator pupillae acts unopposed."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Excellent! The sphincter pupillae is the key muscle — its parasympathetic fibres run superficially on CN III and are compressed first in a palsy, producing a fixed, dilated pupil."
                }
              ],
